m, Essex, England":"Great Waltham, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cornish","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name for someone from the county of Cornwall, from Middle English <i>Cornish</i>, <i>Cornysh</i> formed on the analogy of <i>English</i>, which was usually Normanized as <i>Corneys</i>. Not surprisingly, the surname is common in adjacent Devon, but it is also established as far afield as Suffolk and London."],"variants":[{"name":"Corns","meanings":["English (Staffordshire and Lancashire): variant of   Cornish   or   Corn  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Cornish was born about 1360, in Great Waltham, Essex, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Cornish, was 22 and his mother, Joanne Dungay, was 17. He married Eden Hunt about 1390, in Great Waltham, Essex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"Abt 1360–":"umbes 1360–Surnud","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1345–1410":"1345–1410","Abt 1360":"umbes 1360","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1345":"1345","1410":"1410","1365":"1365","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","Abt 1390":"umbes 1390","1390":"1390","Great Waltham, Essex, England":"Great Waltham, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi